@startuml
title Response and Recovery Workflow
left to right direction

' Palette
' #211951 (deep navy)
' #836FFF (violet)
' #15F5BA (mint)
' #F0F3FF (soft white)

skinparam backgroundColor #F0F3FF
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam defaultFontName Segoe UI
skinparam defaultFontColor #211951
skinparam ArrowColor #211951
skinparam ArrowThickness 1

skinparam activity {
  StartColor #15F5BA
  EndColor #15F5BA
  BarColor #211951
  DiamondBackgroundColor #836FFF
  DiamondBorderColor #211951
  DiamondFontColor #F0F3FF
  BackgroundColor #F0F3FF
  BorderColor #211951
  FontColor #211951
}

start
:Monitoring detects error spikes\nor support receives complaints;
:Incident manager is activated;

if (Is customer impact confirmed?) then (Yes)
  :Classify severity\n(critical/high/medium);
else (No)
  :Continue observation and diagnostics;
  stop
endif

if (Is this a provider-wide issue?) then (Yes)
  :Switch to continuity mode and\nfocus on customer-safe fallback;
else (No)
  :Apply local fix and monitor recovery;
endif

fork
  :Traffic actions:\nRoute users to healthy region;
fork again
  :Application actions:\nEnable degraded mode\n(guest browsing/guest checkout where allowed);
fork again
  :Dependency actions:\nRetry/queue payment requests\nand apply login fallback options;
fork again
  :Communication actions:\nPublish status page update\nand internal incident update;
end fork

if (Are checkout and login stable?) then (Yes)
  :Maintain heightened monitoring;
  :Announce service stabilization;
else (No)
  :Escalate to secondary recovery plan\nand continue mitigations;
endif

:Run post-incident review;
:Track corrective actions and\nschedule continuity test;
stop

legend right
|= Visual Element |= Meaning |
| Start/End (mint) | Workflow begins/ends |
| Decision (violet) | A yes/no choice point |
| Action (soft white) | Concrete step the team performs |
| Arrows (navy) | Order of operations |
endlegend

note bottom
Plain-English guide:
This chart shows what the team does during an outage.
First, they confirm customer impact. Then they decide whether the issue is local or provider-wide.
In parallel, they work on routing, app fallback, external dependency handling, and communication.
They stay in recovery mode until login and checkout are stable.
Finally, they review what happened and improve the plan for next time.
end note

@enduml